b/d/d4/Correlation_examples2.svg/500px-Correlation_examples2.svg.png" decod=
ing=3D"async" width=3D"400" height=3D"183" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-f=
ile-width=3D"506" data-file-height=3D"231"></a><figcaption>Several sets of =
(<i>x</i>,&nbsp;<i>y</i>) points, with the correlation coefficient of <i>x<=
/i> and <i>y</i> for each set. The correlation reflects the strength and di=
rection of a linear relationship (top row), but not the slope of that relat=
ionship (middle row), nor many aspects of nonlinear relationships (bottom r=
ow). N.B.: the figure in the center has a slope of 0 but in that case the c=
orrelation coefficient is undefined because the variance of <i>Y</i> is zer=
o.</figcaption></figure>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics" title=3D"Statist=
ics">statistics</a>, the <b>Pearson correlation coefficient</b> (<b>PCC</b>=
)<sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Pearson_correlation_coefficient#cite_note-3"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>a<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> is a <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Correlation_coefficient" title=3D"Corr=
elation coefficient">correlation coefficient</a> that measures <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Linear"=
>linear</a> correlation between two sets of data. It is the ratio between t=
he <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Covariance" title=3D"Covariance=
">covariance</a> of two variables and the product of their <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Standard_deviation" title=3D"Standard deviation">s=
tandard deviations</a>; thus, it is essentially a normalized measurement of=
 the covariance, such that the result always has a value between =E2=88=921=
 and 1.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Pearson_correlation_coefficient#cite_note-4"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> A k=
ey difference is that unlike covariance, this correlation coefficient does =
not have <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unit_of_measurement" titl=
e=3D"Unit of measurement">units</a>, allowing comparison of the strength of=
 the joint association between different pairs of random variables that do =
not necessarily have the same units.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-5" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pearson_correlation_coefficien=
t#cite_note-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup> As with covariance itself, the measure can only r=
eflect a linear <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Correlation" title=
=3D"Correlation">correlation</a> of variables, and ignores many other types=
 of relationships or correlations. As a simple example, one would expect th=
e age and height of a sample of children from a school to have a Pearson co=
rrelation coefficient significantly greater than 0, but less than 1 (as 1 w=
ould represent an unrealistically perfect correlation).
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Naming_and_history">Naming =
and history</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3D=
Pearson_correlation_coefficient&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D=
"Edit section: Naming and history"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-e=
ditsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>It was developed by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Karl_Pearso=
n" title=3D"Karl Pearson">Karl Pearson</a> from a related idea introduced b=
y <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Francis_Galton" title=3D"Francis=
 Galton">Francis Galton</a> in the 1880s, and for which the mathematical fo=
rmula was derived and published by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Auguste_Bravais" title=3D"Auguste Bravais">Auguste Bravais</a> in 1844.<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-9" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Pearson_correlation_coefficient#cite_note-9"><span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">[</span>b<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-10" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pear=
son_correlation_coefficient#cite_note-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-11"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pearson_corre=
lation_coefficient#cite_note-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-12" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pearson_correlation_co=
efficient#cite_note-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-13" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pearson_correlation_coefficie=
nt#cite_note-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The naming of the coefficient is thus an examp=
le of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stigler%27s_Law" class=3D"mw=
-redirect" title=3D"Stigler's Law">Stigler's Law</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Intuitive_explanation">Intu=
itive explanation</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-edit=
section-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?ti=
tle=3DPearson_correlation_coefficient&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" ti=
tle=3D"Edit section: Intuitive explanation"><span>edit</span></a><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The correlation coefficient can be derived by considering the cosine of =
the angle between two points representing the two sets of x and y co-ordina=
te data.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-14" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Pearson_correlation_coefficient#cite_note-14"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 This expression is therefore a number between -1 and 1 and is equal to uni=
ty when all the points lie on a straight line.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Definition">Definition</h2>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DPearson_correlat=
ion_coefficient&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit section: D=
efinition"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</s=
pan></span></div>
<p>Pearson's correlation coefficient is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Covariance" title=3D"Covariance">covariance</a> of the two variab=
les divided by the product of their standard deviations. The form of the de=
finition involves a "product moment", that is, the mean (the first <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moment_(mathematics)" title=3D"Moment (ma=
thematics)">moment</a> about the origin) of the product of the mean-adjuste=
d random variables; hence the modifier <i>product-moment</i> in the name.<s=
up class=3D"noprint Inline-Template" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Verifiability" title=3D"Wiki=
pedia:Verifiability"><span title=3D"The material near this tag needs to be =
fact-checked with the cited source(s). (February 2024)">verification needed=
</span></a></i>]</sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"For_a_population">For a pop=
ulation</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DPear=
son_correlation_coefficient&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edi=
t section: For a population"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsec=
tion-bracket">]</span></span></div>
