<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Practical_issues">Practical=
 issues</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DPear=
son_correlation_coefficient&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D7" title=3D"Edi=
t section: Practical issues"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsec=
tion-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Under heavy noise conditions, extracting the correlation coefficient bet=
ween two sets of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Random_variables"=
 class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Random variables">stochastic variables</a> =
is nontrivial, in particular where <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Canonical_Correlation_Analysis" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Canonical C=
orrelation Analysis">Canonical Correlation Analysis</a> reports degraded co=
rrelation values due to the heavy noise contributions. A generalization of =
the approach is given elsewhere.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-17" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pearson_correlation_coefficient#c=
ite_note-17"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In case of missing data, Garren derived the <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Maximum_likelihood" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Maximum=
 likelihood">maximum likelihood</a> estimator.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-18" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pearson_correlation=
_coefficient#cite_note-18"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>16<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Some distributions (e.g., <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/S=
table_distribution" title=3D"Stable distribution">stable distributions</a> =
other than a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Normal_distribution" =
title=3D"Normal distribution">normal distribution</a>) do not have a define=
d variance.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Mathematical_properties">Ma=
thematical properties</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-=
editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.ph=
p?title=3DPearson_correlation_coefficient&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D8=
" title=3D"Edit section: Mathematical properties"><span>edit</span></a><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The values of both the sample and population Pearson correlation coeffic=
ients are on or between =E2=88=921 and 1. Correlations equal to +1 or =E2=
=88=921 correspond to data points lying exactly on a line (in the case of t=
he sample correlation), or to a bivariate distribution entirely <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Support_(measure_theory)" title=3D"Support (m=
easure theory)">supported</a> on a line (in the case of the population corr=
elation). The Pearson correlation coefficient is symmetric: corr(<i>X</i>,<=
i>Y</i>)&nbsp;=3D&nbsp;corr(<i>Y</i>,<i>X</i>).
</p><p>A key mathematical property of the Pearson correlation coefficient i=
s that it is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Invariant_estimator" =
title=3D"Invariant estimator">invariant</a> under separate changes in locat=
ion and scale in the two variables. That is, we may transform <i>X</i> to <=
span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i> + <i>bX</i></span> and transform <i>Y</i> t=
o <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>c</i> + <i>dY</i></span>, where <i>a</i>, <i>b=
</i>, <i>c</i>, and <i>d</i> are constants with <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=
b</i>, <i>d</i> &gt; 0</span>, without changing the correlation coefficient=
. (This holds for both the population and sample Pearson correlation coeffi=
cients.) More general linear transformations do change the correlation: see=
 <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pearson_correlation_coefficien=
t#Decorrelation_of_n_random_variables">=C2=A7&nbsp;Decorrelation of n rando=
m variables</a></i> for an application of this. In particular, it might be =
useful to notice that corr(<i>-X</i>,<i>Y</i>)&nbsp;=3D&nbsp;-corr(<i>X</i>=
,<i>Y</i>)
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Interpretation">Interpretat=
ion</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DPearson_=
correlation_coefficient&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D9" title=3D"Edit se=
ction: Interpretation"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-b=
racket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The correlation coefficient ranges from =E2=88=921 to 1. An absolute val=
ue of exactly 1 implies that a linear equation describes the relationship b=
etween <i>X</i> and <i>Y</i> perfectly, with all data points lying on a <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Line_(mathematics)" class=3D"mw-redir=
ect" title=3D"Line (mathematics)">line</a>. The correlation sign is determi=
ned by the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regression_slope" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Regression slope">regression slope</a>: a value o=
f +1 implies that all data points lie on a line for which <i>Y</i> increase=
s as <i>X</i> increases, whereas a value of -1 implies a line where <i>Y</i=
> increases while <i>X</i> decreases.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-STAT_462_19-0" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pearson_correlati=
on_coefficient#cite_note-STAT_462-19"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
17<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> A value of 0 implies that=
 there is no linear dependency between the variables.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-20=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pearson_corr=
elation_coefficient#cite_note-20"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>More generally, <span class=3D"texhtml">(<i>X</i><sub><i>i</i></sub>=
 =E2=88=92 <span style=3D"text-decoration:overline;"><i>X</i></span>)(<i>Y<=
/i><sub><i>i</i></sub> =E2=88=92 <span style=3D"text-decoration:overline;">=
<i>Y</i></span>)</span> is positive if and only if <i>X</i><sub><i>i</i></s=
ub> and <i>Y</i><sub><i>i</i></sub> lie on the same side of their respectiv=
e means. Thus the correlation coefficient is positive if <i>X</i><sub><i>i<=
/i></sub> and <i>Y</i><sub><i>i</i></sub> tend to be simultaneously greater=
 than, or simultaneously less than, their respective means. The correlation=
 coefficient is negative (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anti-cor=
relation" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Anti-correlation">anti-correlation=
</a>) if <i>X</i><sub><i>i</i></sub> and <i>Y</i><sub><i>i</i></sub> tend t=
o lie on opposite sides of their respective means. Moreover, the stronger e=
ither tendency is, the larger is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Absolute_value" title=3D"Absolute value">absolute value</a> of the corre=
lation coefficient.
</p><p>Rodgers and Nicewander<sup id=3D"cite_ref-21" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pearson_correlation_coefficient#cite=
_note-21"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>19<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup> cataloged thirteen ways of interpreting correlation o=
r simple functions of it:
</p>
<ul><li>Function of raw scores and means</li>
<li>Standardized covariance</li>
<li>Standardized slope of the regression line</li>
<li>Geometric mean of the two regression slopes</li>
<li>Square root of the ratio of two variances</li>
<li>Mean cross-product of standardized variables</li>
<li>Function of the angle between two standardized regression lines</li>
<li>Function of the angle between two variable vectors</li>
<li>Rescaled variance of the difference between standardized scores</li>
<li>Estimated from the balloon rule</li>
<li>Related to the bivariate ellipses of isoconcentration</li>
<li>Function of test statistics from designed experiments</li>
<li>Ratio of two means</li></ul>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Geometric_interpretation">G=
eometric interpretation</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"m=
w-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.=
php?title=3DPearson_correlation_coefficient&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=
=3D10" title=3D"Edit section: Geometric interpretation"><span>edit</span></=
a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Regression_lines.png" class=3D"mw-file-descri=
ption"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d=
1/Regression_lines.png/500px-Regression_lines.png" decoding=3D"async" width=
=3D"380" height=3D"331" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"603" d=
ata-file-height=3D"525"></a><figcaption>Regression lines for <span class=3D=
"texhtml"><i>y</i> =3D <i>g</i><sub><i>X</i></sub>(<i>x</i>)</span> [<span =
class=3D"tmp-color" style=3D"color:red">red</span>] and <span class=3D"texh=
tml"><i>x</i> =3D <i>g</i><sub><i>Y</i></sub>(<i>y</i>)</span> [<link rel=
=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r123933449=
4"><span class=3D"tmp-color" style=3D"color:blue">blue</span>]</figcaption>=
</figure>
<p>For uncentered data, there is a relation between the correlation coeffic=
ient and the angle <i>=CF=86</i> between the two regression lines, <span cl=
ass=3D"nowrap"><i>y</i> =3D <i>g</i><sub><i>X</i></sub>(<i>x</i>)</span> an=
d <span class=3D"nowrap"><i>x</i> =3D <i>g</i><sub><i>Y</i></sub>(<i>y</i>)=
</span>, obtained by regressing <i>y</i> on <i>x</i> and <i>x</i> on <i>y</=
i> respectively. (Here, <i>=CF=86</i> is measured counterclockwise within t=
he first quadrant formed around the lines' intersection point if <span clas=
s=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i> &gt; 0</span>, or counterclockwise from the fourth t=
o the second quadrant if <span class=3D"nowrap"><i>r</i> &lt; 0</span>.) On=
e can show<sup id=3D"cite_ref-22" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pearson_correlation_coefficient#cite_note-22"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>20<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p> that if the standard deviations are equal, then <span class=3D"nowrap"><=
i>r</i> =3D sec <i>=CF=86</i> =E2=88=92 tan <i>=CF=86</i></span>, where sec=
 and tan are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trigonometric_functio=
ns" title=3D"Trigonometric functions">trigonometric functions</a>.
</p><p>For centered data (i.e., data which have been shifted by the sample =
means of their respective variables so as to have an average of zero for ea=
ch variable), the correlation coefficient can also be viewed as the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cosine" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Co=
sine">cosine</a> of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Angle" tit=
le=3D"Angle">angle</a> <i>=CE=B8</i> between the two observed <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vector_(geometry)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Vector (geometry)">vectors</a> in <i>N</i>-dimensional space (for <i>N<=
/i> observations of each variable).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-23" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pearson_correlation_coefficien=
t#cite_note-23"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>21<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Both the uncentered (non-Pearson-compliant) and centered correlation=
 coefficients can be determined for a dataset. As an example, suppose five =
countries are found to have gross national products of 1, 2, 3, 5, and 8 bi=
llion dollars, respectively. Suppose these same five countries (in the same=
 order) are found to have 11%, 12%, 13%, 15%, and 18% poverty. Then let <b>=
x</b> and <b>y</b> be ordered 5-element vectors containing the above data: =
<span class=3D"nowrap"><b>x</b> =3D (1, 2, 3, 5, 8)</span> and <span class=
=3D"nowrap"><b>y</b> =3D (0.11, 0.12, 0.13, 0.15, 0.18)</span>.
</p><p>By the usual procedure for finding the angle <i>=CE=B8</i> between t=
wo vectors (see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dot_product" title=
=3D"Dot product">dot product</a>), the <i>uncentered</i> correlation coeffi=
cient is
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e \cos \theta =3D{\frac {\mathbf {x} \cdot \mathbf {y} }{\left\|\mathbf {x}=
 \right\|\left\|\mathbf {y} \right\|}}=3D{\frac {2.93}{{\sqrt {103}}{\sqrt =
{0.0983}}}}=3D0.920814711.}">
