-align: -2.838ex; width:50.152ex; height:6.176ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \c=
os \theta =3D{\frac {\mathbf {x} \cdot \mathbf {y} }{\left\|\mathbf {x} \ri=
ght\|\left\|\mathbf {y} \right\|}}=3D{\frac {2.93}{{\sqrt {103}}{\sqrt {0.0=
983}}}}=3D0.920814711.}"></span></dd></dl>
<p>This uncentered correlation coefficient is identical with the <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cosine_similarity" title=3D"Cosine similarit=
y">cosine similarity</a>. The above data were deliberately chosen to be per=
fectly correlated: <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>y</i> =3D 0.10 + 0.01 <i>x</i=
></span>. The Pearson correlation coefficient must therefore be exactly one=
. Centering the data (shifting <b>x</b> by <span class=3D"texhtml">=E2=84=
=B0(<b>x</b>) =3D 3.8</span> and <b>y</b> by <span class=3D"texhtml">=E2=84=
=B0(<b>y</b>) =3D 0.138</span>) yields <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>x</b> =3D=
 (=E2=88=922.8, =E2=88=921.8, =E2=88=920.8, 1.2, 4.2)</span> and <span clas=
s=3D"texhtml"><b>y</b> =3D (=E2=88=920.028, =E2=88=920.018, =E2=88=920.008,=
 0.012, 0.042)</span>, from which
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
