<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Interpretation_of_the_size_=
of_a_correlation">Interpretation of the size of a correlation</h3><span cla=
ss=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DPearson_correlation_coeff=
icient&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D11" title=3D"Edit section: Interpret=
ation of the size of a correlation"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-=
editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Pearson_correlation_and_prediction_intervals.=
svg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org=
/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a7/Pearson_correlation_and_prediction_intervals.=
svg/250px-Pearson_correlation_and_prediction_intervals.svg.png" decoding=3D=
"async" width=3D"200" height=3D"140" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-wi=
dth=3D"956" data-file-height=3D"670"></a><figcaption>This figure gives a se=
nse of how the usefulness of a Pearson correlation for predicting values va=
ries with its magnitude. Given jointly normal <i>X</i>, <i>Y</i> with corre=
lation <i>=CF=81</i>, <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inli=
ne"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"di=
splay: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D=
"{\displaystyle 1-{\sqrt {1-\rho ^{2}}}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mn>1</mn>
        <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <msqrt>
            <mn>1</mn>
            <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
            <msup>
              <mi>=CF=81<!-- =CF=81 --></mi>
              <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                <mn>2</mn>
              </mrow>
            </msup>
          </msqrt>
        </mrow>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle 1-{\sqrt {1-\=
rho ^{2}}}}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/8d2503071eb5432a487fd7f300442f2cf5fc6073" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -1.671ex; width:12.586ex; height:4.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle 1-=
{\sqrt {1-\rho ^{2}}}}"></span> (plotted here as a function of <i>=CF=81</i=
>) is the factor by which a given <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Prediction_interval" title=3D"Prediction interval">prediction interval</a> =
for <i>Y</i> may be reduced given the corresponding value of <i>X</i>. For =
example, if <i>=CF=81</i> =3D 0.5, then the 95% prediction interval of <i>Y=
</i>|<i>X</i> will be about 13% smaller than the 95% prediction interval of=
 <i>Y</i>.</figcaption></figure>
<p>Several authors have offered guidelines for the interpretation of a corr=
elation coefficient.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Buda_24-0" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pearson_correlation_coefficient#cite_n=
ote-Buda-24"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>22<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Cohen88_25-0" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pearson_correlation_coefficient=
#cite_note-Cohen88-25"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>23<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> However, all such criteria are in some=
 ways arbitrary.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Cohen88_25-1" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pearson_correlation_coefficient#cite_no=
te-Cohen88-25"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>23<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup> The interpretation of a correlation coefficient =
depends on the context and purposes. A correlation of 0.8 may be very low i=
f one is verifying a physical law using high-quality instruments, but may b=
e regarded as very high in the social sciences, where there may be a greate=
r contribution from complicating factors.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Inference">Inference</h2><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DPearson_correlatio=
n_coefficient&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D12" title=3D"Edit section: In=
ference"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</spa=
n></span></div>
<p>Statistical inference based on Pearson's correlation coefficient often f=
ocuses on one of the following two aims:
</p>
<ul><li>One aim is to test the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nul=
l_hypothesis" title=3D"Null hypothesis">null hypothesis</a> that the true c=
orrelation coefficient <i>=CF=81</i> is equal to 0, based on the value of t=
he sample correlation coefficient <i>r</i>.</li>
<li>The other aim is to derive a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C=
onfidence_interval" title=3D"Confidence interval">confidence interval</a> t=
hat, on repeated sampling, has a given probability of containing <i>=CF=81<=
/i>.</li></ul>
<p>Methods of achieving one or both of these aims are discussed below.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Using_a_permutation_test">U=
sing a permutation test</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"m=
w-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.=
php?title=3DPearson_correlation_coefficient&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=
=3D13" title=3D"Edit section: Using a permutation test"><span>edit</span></=
a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Permutation_test" title=3D"Perm=
utation test">Permutation tests</a> provide a direct approach to performing=
 hypothesis tests and constructing confidence intervals. A permutation test=
 for Pearson's correlation coefficient involves the following two steps:=20
</p>
<ol><li>Using the original paired data (<i>x</i><sub><i>i</i></sub>,&nbsp;<=
i>y</i><sub><i>i</i></sub>), randomly redefine the pairs to create a new da=
ta set (<i>x</i><sub><i>i</i></sub>,&nbsp;<i>y</i><sub><i>i<span class=3D"n=
owrap" style=3D"padding-left:0.05em;">=E2=80=B2</span></i></sub>), where th=
e <i>i<span class=3D"nowrap" style=3D"padding-left:0.05em;">=E2=80=B2</span=
></i> are a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Permutation" title=3D"=
Permutation">permutation</a> of the set {1,...,<i>n</i>}.  The permutation =
<i>i<span class=3D"nowrap" style=3D"padding-left:0.05em;">=E2=80=B2</span><=
/i> is selected randomly, with equal probabilities placed on all <i>n</i>! =
possible permutations.  This is equivalent to drawing the <i>i<span class=
=3D"nowrap" style=3D"padding-left:0.05em;">=E2=80=B2</span></i> randomly wi=
thout replacement from the set {1, ..., <i>n</i>}.  In <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bootstrapping_(statistics)" title=3D"Bootstrapping (st=
atistics)">bootstrapping</a>, a closely related approach, the <i>i</i> and =
the <i>i<span class=3D"nowrap" style=3D"padding-left:0.05em;">=E2=80=B2</sp=
an></i> are equal and drawn with replacement from {1, ..., <i>n</i>};</li>
<li>Construct a correlation coefficient <i>r</i> from the randomized data.<=
/li></ol>
<p>To perform the permutation test, repeat steps&nbsp;(1) and (2) a large n=
umber of times.  The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P-value" titl=
e=3D"P-value">p-value</a> for the permutation test is the proportion of the=
 <i>r</i> values generated in step&nbsp;(2) that are larger than the Pearso=
n correlation coefficient that was calculated from the original data.  Here=
 "larger" can mean either that the value is larger in magnitude, or larger =
in signed value, depending on whether a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Two-tailed_test" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Two-tailed test">two-=
sided</a> or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/One-sided_test" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"One-sided test">one-sided</a> test is desired.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Using_a_bootstrap">Using a =
bootstrap</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-=
bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DPe=
arson_correlation_coefficient&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D14" title=3D"=
Edit section: Using a bootstrap"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-edi=
tsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bootstrapping_(statistics)"=
 title=3D"Bootstrapping (statistics)">bootstrap</a> can be used to construc=
t confidence intervals for Pearson's correlation coefficient.  In the "non-=
parametric" bootstrap, <i>n</i> pairs (<i>x</i><sub><i>i</i></sub>,&nbsp;<i=
>y</i><sub><i>i</i></sub>) are resampled "with replacement" from the observ=
ed set of <i>n</i> pairs, and the correlation coefficient <i>r</i> is calcu=
lated based on the resampled data.  This process is repeated a large number=
 of times, and the empirical distribution of the resampled <i>r</i> values =
are used to approximate the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sampli=
ng_distribution" title=3D"Sampling distribution">sampling distribution</a> =
of the statistic.  A 95% <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Confidenc=
e_interval" title=3D"Confidence interval">confidence interval</a> for <i>=
=CF=81</i> can be defined as the interval spanning from the 2.5th to the 97=
.5th <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Percentile" title=3D"Percenti=
le">percentile</a> of the resampled <i>r</i> values.
</p>
