<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Sensitivity_to_the_data_dis=
tribution">Sensitivity to the data distribution</h2><span class=3D"mw-edits=
ection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DPearson_correlation_coefficient&amp;act=
ion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D20" title=3D"Edit section: Sensitivity to the data=
 distribution"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">=
]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Further information: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Correlation_a=
nd_dependence#Sensitivity_to_the_data_distribution" class=3D"mw-redirect" t=
itle=3D"Correlation and dependence">Correlation and dependence =C2=A7&nbsp;=
Sensitivity to the data distribution</a></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Existence">Existence</h3><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DPearson_correlatio=
n_coefficient&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D21" title=3D"Edit section: Ex=
istence"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</spa=
n></span></div>
<p>The population Pearson correlation coefficient is defined in terms of <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moment_(mathematics)" title=3D"Momen=
t (mathematics)">moments</a>, and therefore exists for any bivariate <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability_distribution" title=3D"Proba=
bility distribution">probability distribution</a> for which the <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_population" title=3D"Statistical =
population">population</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Covaria=
nce" title=3D"Covariance">covariance</a> is defined and the <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marginal_distribution" title=3D"Marginal distribu=
tion">marginal</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Population_vari=
ance" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Population variance">population varian=
ces</a> are defined and are non-zero. Some probability distributions, such =
as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cauchy_distribution" title=
=3D"Cauchy distribution">Cauchy distribution</a>, have undefined variance a=
nd hence =CF=81 is not defined if <i>X</i> or <i>Y</i> follows such a distr=
ibution. In some practical applications, such as those involving data suspe=
cted to follow a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heavy-tailed_dist=
ribution" title=3D"Heavy-tailed distribution">heavy-tailed distribution</a>=
, this is an important consideration.  However, the existence of the correl=
ation coefficient is usually not a concern; for instance, if the range of t=
he distribution is bounded, =CF=81 is always defined.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Sample_size">Sample size</h=
3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</=
span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DPearson_correl=
ation_coefficient&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D22" title=3D"Edit section=
: Sample size"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">=
]</span></span></div>
<ul><li>If the sample size is moderate or large and the population is norma=
l, then, in the case of the bivariate <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Normal_distribution" title=3D"Normal distribution">normal distribution<=
/a>, the sample correlation coefficient is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Maximum_likelihood_estimate" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Ma=
ximum likelihood estimate">maximum likelihood estimate</a> of the populatio=
n correlation coefficient, and is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Asymptotic_distribution" title=3D"Asymptotic distribution">asymptotically</=
a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bias_of_an_estimator" title=3D"=
Bias of an estimator">unbiased</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Efficiency_(statistics)" title=3D"Efficiency (statistics)">efficient</=
a>, which roughly means that it is impossible to construct a more accurate =
estimate than the sample correlation coefficient.</li>
<li>If the sample size is large and the population is not normal, then the =
sample correlation coefficient remains approximately unbiased, but may not =
be efficient.</li>
<li>If the sample size is large, then the sample correlation coefficient is=
 a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Consistent_estimator" title=3D"=
Consistent estimator">consistent estimator</a> of the population correlatio=
n coefficient as long as the sample means, variances, and covariance are co=
nsistent (which is guaranteed when the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Law_of_large_numbers" title=3D"Law of large numbers">law of large numb=
ers</a> can be applied).</li>
<li>If the sample size is small, then the sample correlation coefficient <i=
>r</i> is not an unbiased estimate of <i>=CF=81</i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Rea=
lCorBasic_15-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Pearson_correlation_coefficient#cite_note-RealCorBasic-15"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Th=
e adjusted correlation coefficient must be used instead: see elsewhere in t=
his article for the definition.</li>
<li>Correlations can be different for imbalanced <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Dichotomous_variable" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Dichoto=
mous variable">dichotomous</a> data when there is variance error in sample.=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-35" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Pearson_correlation_coefficient#cite_note-35"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>33<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li></u=
l>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Robustness">Robustness</h3>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DPearson_correlat=
ion_coefficient&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D23" title=3D"Edit section: =
Robustness"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</=
span></span></div>
<p>Like many commonly used statistics, the sample <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Statistic" title=3D"Statistic">statistic</a> <i>r</i> is no=
t <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robust_statistics" title=3D"Robu=
st statistics">robust</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-wilcox_36-0" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pearson_correlation_coefficien=
t#cite_note-wilcox-36"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>34<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> so its value can be misleading if <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Outlier" title=3D"Outlier">outliers</a=
> are present.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-37" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pearson_correlation_coefficient#cite_note-37"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>35<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-38" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Pearson_correlation_coefficient#cite_note-38"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>36<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 Specifically, the PMCC is neither distributionally robust,<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-39" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pearso=
n_correlation_coefficient#cite_note-39"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>37<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> nor outlier resistant<s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-wilcox_36-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Pearson_correlation_coefficient#cite_note-wilcox-36"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>34<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup> (see <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robust_statistics#D=
efinition" title=3D"Robust statistics">Robust statistics =C2=A7&nbsp;Defini=
tion</a></i>). Inspection of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/S=
catterplot" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Scatterplot">scatterplot</a> bet=
ween <i>X</i> and <i>Y</i> will typically reveal a situation where lack of =
robustness might be an issue, and in such cases it may be advisable to use =
a robust measure of association. Note however that while most robust estima=
tors of association measure <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statis=
tical_dependence" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Statistical dependence">st=
atistical dependence</a> in some way, they are generally not interpretable =
on the same scale as the Pearson correlation coefficient.
</p><p>Statistical inference for Pearson's correlation coefficient is sensi=
tive to the data distribution.  Exact tests, and asymptotic tests based on =
the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fisher_transformation" title=
=3D"Fisher transformation">Fisher transformation</a> can be applied if the =
data are approximately normally distributed, but may be misleading otherwis=
e.  In some situations, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bootst=
rapping_(statistics)" title=3D"Bootstrapping (statistics)">bootstrap</a> ca=
n be applied to construct confidence intervals, and <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Permutation_test" title=3D"Permutation test">permutation =
tests</a> can be applied to carry out hypothesis tests.  These <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Non-parametric_statistics" class=3D"mw-redirec=
t" title=3D"Non-parametric statistics">non-parametric</a> approaches may gi=
ve more meaningful results in some situations where bivariate normality doe=
s not hold.  However the standard versions of these approaches rely on <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exchangeable_random_variables" title=
=3D"Exchangeable random variables">exchangeability</a> of the data, meaning=
 that there is no ordering or grouping of the data pairs being analyzed tha=
t might affect the behavior of the correlation estimate.
</p><p>A stratified analysis is one way to either accommodate a lack of biv=
ariate normality, or to isolate the correlation resulting from one factor w=
hile controlling for another.  If <i>W</i> represents cluster membership or=
 another factor that it is desirable to control, we can <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stratified_sampling" title=3D"Stratified sampling">st=
ratify</a> the data based on the value of <i>W</i>, then calculate a correl=
ation coefficient within each stratum.  The stratum-level estimates can the=
n be combined to estimate the overall correlation while controlling for <i>=
W</i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-40" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Pearson_correlation_coefficient#cite_note-40"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>38<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Variants">Variants</h2><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DPearson_correlation_=
coefficient&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D24" title=3D"Edit section: Vari=
ants"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span><=
/span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Correlation_and_dependen=
ce#Other_measures_of_dependence_among_random_variables" class=3D"mw-redirec=
t" title=3D"Correlation and dependence">Correlation and dependence =C2=A7&n=
bsp;Other measures of dependence among random variables</a></div>
<p>Variations of the correlation coefficient can be calculated for differen=
t purposes. Here are some examples.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Adjusted_correlation_coeffi=
cient">Adjusted correlation coefficient</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection">=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/w/index.php?title=3DPearson_correlation_coefficient&amp;action=3Ded=
it&amp;section=3D25" title=3D"Edit section: Adjusted correlation coefficien=
t"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></sp=
an></div>
<p>The sample correlation coefficient <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D=
"font-style:italic;">r</span> is not an unbiased estimate of <span class=3D=
"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CF=81</span>. For data that fo=
llows a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bivariate_normal_distribut=
ion" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Bivariate normal distribution">bivariat=
e normal distribution</a>, the expectation <span class=3D"texhtml">E[<i>r</=
i>]</span> for the sample correlation coefficient  <span class=3D"texhtml m=
var" style=3D"font-style:italic;">r</span> of a normal bivariate is<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-41" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Pearson_correlation_coefficient#cite_note-41"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>39<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e \operatorname {\mathbb {E} } \left[r\right]=3D\rho -{\frac {\rho \left(1-=
\rho ^{2}\right)}{2n}}+\cdots ,\quad }">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-OP MJX-fixedlimits">
