{X,Y}=3D1-\rho _{X,Y}.}"></span></dd></dl>
<p>Considering that the Pearson correlation coefficient falls between [=E2=
=88=921, +1], the Pearson distance lies in [0, 2]. The Pearson distance has=
 been used in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cluster_analysis" ti=
tle=3D"Cluster analysis">cluster analysis</a> and data detection for commun=
ications and storage with unknown gain and offset.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-47" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pearson_correla=
tion_coefficient#cite_note-47"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>45<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The Pearson "distance" defined this way assigns distance greater tha=
n 1 to negative correlations. In reality, both strong positive correlation =
and negative correlations are meaningful, so care must be taken when Pearso=
n "distance" is used for nearest neighbor algorithm as such algorithm will =
only include neighbors with positive correlation and exclude neighbors with=
 negative correlation. Alternatively, an absolute valued distance, <span cl=
ass=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-ma=
thml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"h=
ttp://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle d_{X,Y}=3D1-|\=
rho _{X,Y}|}">
