=80)</span>, it is possible to define a circular analog of Pearson's coeffi=
cient.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-SRJ_48-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pearson_correlation_coefficient#cite_note-SRJ-48"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>46<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup> This is done by transforming data points in <i>X</i> and <i>Y</i> =
with a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sine" class=3D"mw-redirect"=
 title=3D"Sine">sine</a> function such that the correlation coefficient is =
given as:
</p>
