<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Decorrelation_of_n_random_v=
ariables">Decorrelation of <i>n</i> random variables</h2><span class=3D"mw-=
editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DPearson_correlation_coefficient&am=
p;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D33" title=3D"Edit section: Decorrelation of n=
 random variables"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brack=
et">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Decorrelation" title=
=3D"Decorrelation">Decorrelation</a></div>
<p>It is always possible to remove the correlations between all pairs of an=
 arbitrary number of random variables by using a data transformation, even =
if the relationship between the variables is nonlinear. A presentation of t=
his result for population distributions is given by Cox &amp; Hinkley.<sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-51" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Pearson_correlation_coefficient#cite_note-51"><span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">[</span>49<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>A corresponding result exists for reducing the sample correlations t=
o zero. Suppose a vector of <i>n</i> random variables is observed <i>m</i> =
times. Let <i>X</i> be a matrix where <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-m=
ath-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a=
11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/Ma=
thML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle X_{i,j}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <msub>
          <mi>X</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>i</mi>
            <mo>,</mo>
            <mi>j</mi>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle X_{i,j}}</ann=
otation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/b2b9e6670d691d42489f7be6e034cbcca7a92f03" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -1.005ex; width:3.859ex; height:2.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle X_{=
i,j}}"></span> is the <i>j</i>th variable of observation <i>i</i>. Let <spa=
n class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-mat=
h-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=
=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle Z_{m,m}}"=
>
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <msub>
          <mi>Z</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>m</mi>
            <mo>,</mo>
            <mi>m</mi>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle Z_{m,m}}</ann=
otation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/e40ff160c7b41d1bcc4a806d848128347d3c38f3" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -1.005ex; width:5.163ex; height:2.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle Z_{=
m,m}}"></span> be an <i>m</i> by <i>m</i> square matrix with every element =
1. Then <i>D</i> is the data transformed so every random variable has zero =
mean, and <i>T</i> is the data transformed so all variables have zero mean =
and zero correlation with all other variables =E2=80=93 the sample <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Correlation_matrix" class=3D"mw-redirect"=
 title=3D"Correlation matrix">correlation matrix</a> of <i>T</i> will be th=
e identity matrix. This has to be further divided by the standard deviation=
 to get unit variance. The transformed variables will be uncorrelated, even=
 though they may not be <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistica=
l_independence" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Statistical independence">in=
dependent</a>.
</p>
